## 1. Summary ##

We have three main principles in finishing the project. Our first principle is our functions should be able to adjust themselves to the input datasets automatically. we should try to create a series of functions that can really be used as tools instead of just working on a specific dataset or situation. The second principle we value is to give users enough permissions to customize their images. Otherwise the professionalism of this function will decrease. For the creative part, We have learnt in class that we cannot just add useless decorations into the graph, which will only cause interference to users. Our innovation should be able to convey some information contained in the data in a better way. That is our third principle.



## 2.  Initially Preparation and Division of Labor for the Project ##



### 2.1 How we design the project ###

When we started to design the project, we realized that these functions should work as "wheels". A type of wheel can carry different cars and roll over different roads. So the automatic adjustment inside the function should at least containing the size of whole figure and width of lines. Otherwise the graph might looks ridiculous while the magnitude of data changes rapidly.

We want to provide enough parameters for the user to customize their graphs. Some of the parameters should be mandatory for the user like "data". Because it is almost impossible for us to generate a box plot without meaningful data. Some of parameters like "color" and "line_style" should be optional for the user. We will set default values on these parameters for the user incase they just want to get a boxplot graph quickly without too much customization. We also considered the possibility that the user do not input parameters correctly. We need to find a way of tolerating some user mistakes or tell the user what to do is properly.

## 5. The Introduction of Function "creative_boxplot" ##

### 5.1 The introduction of our "creative" idea and how the idea related to class ###

We have learnt in class that **"Show data variation, not design variation"** and **"Graphics must not quote data out of context" **. So We are trying to find a way to represent some really-exist and important feature of data. So we pick the gradient color to show the density of data. It is useful and do not disturb the user too much.
The "creative boxplot" function has the same basic parameters as "info-boxplot". Besides, the "creative" part in this function is we use gradient color as the facecolor of the box. The saturation of the gradient color depends on the data density nearby(in a small interval). Therefore, the distribution of data can be intuitively observed through the concentration of color. We know that the density of data in a small interval is a numerical value depends on the total amount of data. So we use the share of data in the interval instead of just data amount in the interval to represent data density. We also give the user power to select their own color via a RGB tuple as a parameter. If the user do not use this parameter, we set the default value at (0.1, 0.7, 0,7), which is basically an oliver-green color. Here is an example graph generated by four series of random data. ![picture]

### 5.3 Difficulties we have met and how did we fix them ###

For the stability of the function, we have to consider an extreme case: all the data are concentrated in a small interval, which will cause this parameter to be greater than 1 and cause an error. We have tried many mathematical methods to create a new mapping methods to avoid this situation, but none of these methods work well. Finally, we enforce that when the calculated parameter value is greater than 1, force it to equal 1 and then pass it in.
